ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Readers are referred to the Japanese website, where the western blots and
histochemistry of the first "atypical" case are displayed:
<http://www.mhlw.go.jp/houdou/2003/10/h1006-2.html> for further details,
see posting 20031007.25110.
At present, 5 rapid BSE tests are approved by the European Commission for
use in brain material collected from dead animals: Prionics Check Western,
Bio-Rad TeSeE (previously Bio-Rad Platelia), Enfer, Prionics Check LIA and
InPro CDI-5. All 5 have gone through laboratory evaluation and field tests
prior to their approval. They are designed to detect BSE in brain material
collected from animals at the slaughterhouse or those that have died on the
farm. So far, tests designed to detect BSE in live animals have not been
evaluated. Reportedly, the BSE rapid test applied within the national
surveillance in Japan is the Bio-Rad TeSeE test.
Japan is the only country where tests are not limited to bovines older than
24 (or 30) months, but include all animals arriving at slaughterhouses.-
Mod.AS]
